# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lead-optimization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] In the fields of medicine, biotechnology, and pharmacology, **drug discovery** is the process by which new candidate medications are discovered.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Historically, drugs were discovered by identifying the active ingredient from traditional remedies or by serendipitous discovery, as with penicillin.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] More recently, chemical libraries of synthetic small molecules, natural products, or extracts were screened in intact cells or whole organisms to identify substances that had a desirable therapeutic effect in a process known as classical pharmacology.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Hits from these screens are then tested in cells and then in animals for efficacy.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Modern drug discovery involves the identification of screening hits, medicinal chemistry, and optimization of those hits to increase the affinity, selectivity (to reduce the potential of side effects), efficacy and potency, metabolic stability (to increase the half-life), and oral bioavailability.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Once a compound that fulfills all of these requirements has been identified, the process of drug development can continue.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] If successful, clinical trials are developed.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Modern drug discovery is thus usually a capital-intensive process that involves large investments by pharmaceutical industry corporations as well as national governments (who provide grants and loan guarantees).
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Despite advances in technology and understanding of biological systems, drug discovery is still a lengthy, "expensive, difficult, and inefficient process" with low rate of new therapeutic discovery.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] In 2010, the research and development cost of each new molecular entity was about US$1.8 billion.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] In the 21st century, basic discovery research is funded primarily by governments and by philanthropic organizations, while late-stage development is funded primarily by pharmaceutical companies or venture capitalists.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] To be allowed to come to market, drugs must undergo several successful phases of clinical trials, and pass through a new drug approval process, called the New Drug Application in the United States.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Discovering drugs that may be a commercial success, or a public health success, involves a complex interaction between investors, industry, academia, patent laws, regulatory exclusivity, marketing, and the need to balance secrecy with communication.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Meanwhile, for disorders whose rarity means that no large commercial success or public health effect can be expected, the orphan drug funding process ensures that people who experience those disorders can have some hope of pharmacotherapeutic advances.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] The idea that the effect of a drug in the human body is mediated by specific interactions of the drug molecule with biological macromolecules, (proteins or nucleic acids in most cases) led scientists to the conclusion that individual chemicals are required for the biological activity of the drug.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] This made for the beginning of the modern era in pharmacology, as pure chemicals, instead of crude extracts of medicinal plants, became the standard drugs.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Examples of drug compounds isolated from crude preparations are morphine, the active agent in opium, and digoxin, a heart stimulant originating from *Digitalis lanata*.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Organic chemistry also led to the synthesis of many of the natural products isolated from biological sources.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Historically, substances, whether crude extracts or purified chemicals, were screened for biological activity without knowledge of the biological target.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Only after an active substance was identified was an effort made to identify the target.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] This approach is known as classical pharmacology, forward pharmacology, or phenotypic drug discovery.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Later, small molecules were synthesized to specifically target a known physiological/pathological pathway, avoiding the mass screening of banks of stored compounds.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] This led to great success, such as the work of Gertrude Elion and George H.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Hitchings on purine metabolism, the work of James Black on beta blockers and cimetidine, and the discovery of statins by Akira Endo.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Cloning of human proteins made possible the screening of large libraries of compounds against specific targets thought to be linked to specific diseases.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] This approach is known as reverse pharmacology and is the most frequently used approach today.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] In the 2020s, qubit and quantum computing started to be used to reduce the time needed to drug discovery.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] A "target" is produced within the pharmaceutical industry.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Generally, the "target" is the naturally existing cellular or molecular structure involved in the pathology of interest where the drug-in-development is meant to act.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] However, the distinction between a "new" and "established" target can be made without a full understanding of just what a "target" is.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] This distinction is typically made by pharmaceutical companies engaged in the discovery and development of therapeutics.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] In an estimate from 2011, 435 human genome products were identified as therapeutic drug targets of FDA-approved drugs.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] "Established targets" are those for which there is a good scientific understanding, supported by a lengthy publication history, of both how the target functions in normal physiology and how it is involved in human pathology.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] This does not imply that the mechanism of action of drugs that are thought to act through a particular established target is fully understood.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Rather, "established" relates directly to the amount of background information available on a target, in particular functional information.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] In general, "new targets" are all those targets that are not "established targets" but which have been or are the subject of drug discovery efforts.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] The majority of targets selected for drug discovery efforts are proteins, such as G-protein-coupled receptors (GPCRs) and protein kinases.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] The process of finding a new drug against a chosen target for a particular disease usually involves high-throughput screening (HTS), wherein large libraries of chemicals are tested for their ability to modify the target.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] For example, if the target is a novel GPCR, compounds will be screened for their ability to inhibit or stimulate that receptor (see antagonist and agonist): if the target is a protein kinase, the chemicals will be tested for their ability to inhibit that kinase.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Another function of HTS is to show how selective the compounds are for the chosen target, as one wants to find a molecule which will interfere with only the chosen target, but not other, related targets.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] To this end, other screening runs will be made to see whether the "hits" against the chosen target will interfere with other related targets – this is the process of cross-screening.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Cross-screening is useful because the more unrelated targets a compound hits, the more likely that off-target toxicity will occur with that compound once it reaches the clinic.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] It is unlikely that a perfect drug candidate will emerge from these early screening runs.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] It is often observed that several compounds are found to have some degree of activity, and if these compounds share common chemical features, one or more pharmacophores can then be developed.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] This process will require several iterative screening runs, during which, it is hoped, the properties of the new molecular entities will improve, and allow the favoured compounds to go forward to in vitro and in vivo testing for activity in the disease model of choice.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Amongst the physicochemical properties associated with drug absorption include ionization (pKa), and solubility; permeability can be determined by PAMPA and Caco-2.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] PAMPA is attractive as an early screen due to the low consumption of drug and the low cost compared to tests such as Caco-2, gastrointestinal tract (GIT) and Blood–brain barrier (BBB) with which there is a high correlation.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] A range of parameters can be used to assess the quality of a compound, or a series of compounds, as proposed in the Lipinski's Rule of Five.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Such parameters include calculated properties such as cLogP to estimate lipophilicity, molecular weight, polar surface area and measured properties, such as potency, in-vitro measurement of enzymatic clearance etc.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Some descriptors such as ligand efficiency (LE) and lipophilic efficiency (LiPE) combine such parameters to assess druglikeness.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] While HTS is a commonly used method for novel drug discovery, it is not the only method.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] It is often possible to start from a molecule which already has some of the desired properties.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Such a molecule might be extracted from a natural product or even be a drug on the market which could be improved upon (so-called "me too" drugs).
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Other methods, such as virtual high throughput screening, where screening is done using computer-generated models and attempting to "dock" virtual libraries to a target, are also often used.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Another method for drug discovery is *de novo* drug design, in which a prediction is made of the sorts of chemicals that might (e.g.) fit into an active site of the target enzyme.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] For example, virtual screening and computer-aided drug design are often used to identify new chemical moieties that may interact with a target protein.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Molecular modelling and molecular dynamics simulations can be used as a guide to improve the potency and properties of new drug leads.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] There is also a paradigm shift in the drug discovery community to shift away from HTS, which is expensive and may only cover limited chemical space, to the screening of smaller libraries (maximum a few thousand compounds).
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] These include fragment-based lead discovery (FBDD) and protein-directed dynamic combinatorial chemistry.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] The ligands in these approaches are usually much smaller, and they bind to the target protein with weaker binding affinity than hits that are identified from HTS.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Further modifications through organic synthesis into lead compounds are often required.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Such modifications are often guided by protein X-ray crystallography of the protein-fragment complex.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] The advantages of these approaches are that they allow more efficient screening and the compound library, although small, typically covers a large chemical space when compared to HTS.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Phenotypic screens have also provided new chemical starting points in drug discovery.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] A variety of models have been used including yeast, zebrafish, worms, immortalized cell lines, primary cell lines, patient-derived cell lines and whole animal models.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] These screens are designed to find compounds which reverse a disease phenotype such as death, protein aggregation, mutant protein expression, or cell proliferation as examples in a more holistic cell model or organism.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Smaller screening sets are often used for these screens, especially when the models are expensive or time-consuming to run.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] In many cases, the exact mechanism of action of hits from these screens is unknown and may require extensive target deconvolution experiments to ascertain.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] The growth of the field of chemoproteomics has provided numerous strategies to identify drug targets in these cases.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Once a lead compound series has been established with sufficient target potency and selectivity and favourable drug-like properties, one or two compounds will then be proposed for drug development.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] The best of these is generally called the lead compound, while the other will be designated as the "backup".
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] These decisions are generally supported by computational modelling innovations.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Traditionally, many drugs and other chemicals with biological activity have been discovered by studying chemicals that organisms create to affect the activity of other organisms for survival.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Despite the rise of combinatorial chemistry as an integral part of lead discovery process, natural products still play a major role as starting material for drug discovery.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] A 2007 report found that of the 974 small molecule new chemical entities developed between 1981 and 2006, 63% were natural derived or semisynthetic derivatives of natural products.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] For certain therapy areas, such as antimicrobials, antineoplastics, antihypertensive and anti-inflammatory drugs, the numbers were higher.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Natural products may be useful as a source of novel chemical structures for modern techniques of development of antibacterial therapies.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Many secondary metabolites produced by plants have potential therapeutic medicinal properties.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] These secondary metabolites contain, bind to, and modify the function of proteins (receptors, enzymes, etc.).
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Consequently, plant derived natural products have often been used as the starting point for drug discovery.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Until the Renaissance, the vast majority of drugs in Western medicine were plant-derived extracts.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] This has resulted in a pool of information about the potential of plant species as important sources of starting materials for drug discovery.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Botanical knowledge about different metabolites and hormones that are produced in different anatomical parts of the plant (e.g. roots, leaves, and flowers) are crucial for correctly identifying bioactive and pharmacological plant properties.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Identifying new drugs and getting them approved for market has proved to be a stringent process due to regulations set by national drug regulatory agencies.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Jasmonates are important in responses to injury and intracellular signals.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] They induce apoptosis and protein cascade via proteinase inhibitor, have defense functions, and regulate plant responses to different biotic and abiotic stresses.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Jasmonates also have the ability to directly act on mitochondrial membranes by inducing membrane depolarization via release of metabolites.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Jasmonate derivatives (JAD) are also important in wound response and tissue regeneration in plant cells.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] They have also been identified to have anti-aging effects on human epidermal layer.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] It is suspected that they interact with proteoglycans (PG) and glycosaminoglycan (GAG) polysaccharides, which are essential extracellular matrix (ECM) components to help remodel the ECM.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] The discovery of JADs on skin repair has introduced newfound interest in the effects of these plant hormones in therapeutic medicinal application.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Salicylic acid (SA), a phytohormone, was initially derived from willow bark and has since been identified in many species.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] It is an important player in plant immunity, although its role is still not fully understood by scientists.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] They are involved in disease and immunity responses in plant and animal tissues.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] They have salicylic acid binding proteins (SABPs) that have shown to affect multiple animal tissues.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] The first discovered medicinal properties of the isolated compound was involved in pain and fever management.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] They also play an active role in the suppression of cell proliferation.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] They have the ability to induce death in lymphoblastic leukemia and other human cancer cells.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] One of the most common drugs derived from salicylates is aspirin, also known as acetylsalicylic acid, with anti-inflammatory and anti-pyretic properties.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Some drugs used in modern medicine have been discovered in animals or are based on compounds found in animals.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] For example, the anticoagulant drugs, hirudin and its synthetic congener, bivalirudin, are based on saliva chemistry of the leech, *Hirudo medicinalis*.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Used to treat type 2 diabetes, exenatide was developed from saliva compounds of the Gila monster, a venomous lizard.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Microbes compete for living space and nutrients.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] To survive in these conditions, many microbes have developed abilities to prevent competing species from proliferating.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Microbes are the main source of antimicrobial drugs.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Streptomyces isolates have been such a valuable source of antibiotics, that they have been called medicinal molds.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] The classic example of an antibiotic discovered as a defense mechanism against another microbe is penicillin in bacterial cultures contaminated by *Penicillium* fungi in 1928.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Marine environments are potential sources for new bioactive agents.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Arabinose nucleosides discovered from marine invertebrates in 1950s, demonstrated for the first time that sugar moieties other than ribose and deoxyribose can yield bioactive nucleoside structures.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] It took until 2004 when the first marine-derived drug was approved.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] For example, the cone snail toxin ziconotide, also known as Prialt treats severe neuropathic pain.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Several other marine-derived agents are now in clinical trials for indications such as cancer, anti-inflammatory use and pain.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] One class of these agents are bryostatin-like compounds, under investigation as anti-cancer therapy.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] As above mentioned, combinatorial chemistry was a key technology enabling the efficient generation of large screening libraries for the needs of high-throughput screening.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] However, now, after two decades of combinatorial chemistry, it has been pointed out that despite the increased efficiency in chemical synthesis, no increase in lead or drug candidates has been reached.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] This has led to analysis of chemical characteristics of combinatorial chemistry products, compared to existing drugs or natural products.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] The chemoinformatics concept chemical diversity, depicted as distribution of compounds in the chemical space based on their physicochemical characteristics, is often used to describe the difference between the combinatorial chemistry libraries and natural products.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] The synthetic, combinatorial library compounds seem to cover only a limited and quite uniform chemical space, whereas existing drugs and particularly natural products, exhibit much greater chemical diversity, distributing more evenly to the chemical space.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Other chemical differences between these two groups include the nature of heteroatoms (O and N enriched in natural products, and S and halogen atoms more often present in synthetic compounds), as well as level of non-aromatic unsaturation (higher in natural products).
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] As both structure rigidity and chirality are well-established factors in medicinal chemistry known to enhance compounds specificity and efficacy as a drug, it has been suggested that natural products compare favourably to today's combinatorial chemistry libraries as potential lead molecules.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Two main approaches exist for the finding of new bioactive chemical entities from natural sources.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] The first is sometimes referred to as random collection and screening of material, but the collection is far from random.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Biological (often botanical) knowledge is often used to identify families that show promise.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] This approach is effective because only a small part of the earth's biodiversity has ever been tested for pharmaceutical activity.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Also, organisms living in a species-rich environment need to evolve defensive and competitive mechanisms to survive.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Those mechanisms might be exploited in the development of beneficial drugs.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] A collection of plant, animal and microbial samples from rich ecosystems can potentially give rise to novel biological activities worth exploiting in the drug development process.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] One example of successful use of this strategy is the screening for antitumor agents by the National Cancer Institute, which started in the 1960s.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Paclitaxel was identified from Pacific yew tree *Taxus brevifolia*.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Paclitaxel showed anti-tumour activity by a previously undescribed mechanism (stabilization of microtubules) and is now approved for clinical use for the treatment of lung, breast, and ovarian cancer, as well as for Kaposi's sarcoma.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Early in the 21st century, Cabazitaxel (made by Sanofi, a French firm), another relative of taxol has been shown effective against prostate cancer, also because it works by preventing the formation of microtubules, which pull the chromosomes apart in dividing cells (such as cancer cells).
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Camptotheca (Camptothecin · Topotecan · Irinotecan · Rubitecan · Belotecan); 2.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Podophyllum (Etoposide · Teniposide); 3a.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Anthracyclines (Aclarubicin · Daunorubicin · Doxorubicin · Epirubicin · Idarubicin · Amrubicin · Pirarubicin · Valrubicin · Zorubicin); 3b.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Anthracenediones (Mitoxantrone · Pixantrone).
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] The second main approach involves ethnobotany, the study of the general use of plants in society, and ethnopharmacology, an area inside ethnobotany, which is focused specifically on medicinal uses.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Artemisinin, an antimalarial agent from sweet wormtree *Artemisia annua*, used in Chinese medicine since 200BC is one drug used as part of combination therapy for multiresistant *Plasmodium falciparum*.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] The elucidation of the chemical structure is critical to avoid the re-discovery of a chemical agent that is already known for its structure and chemical activity.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Mass spectrometry is a method in which individual compounds are identified based on their mass/charge ratio, after ionization.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Chemical compounds exist in nature as mixtures, so the combination of liquid chromatography and mass spectrometry (LC-MS) is often used to separate the individual chemicals.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Databases of mass spectra for known compounds are available and can be used to assign a structure to an unknown mass spectrum.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] Nuclear magnetic resonance spectroscopy is the primary technique for determining chemical structures of natural products.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] NMR yields information about individual hydrogen and carbon atoms in the structure, allowing detailed reconstruction of the molecule's architecture.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] When a drug is developed with evidence throughout its history of research to show it is safe and effective for the intended use in the United States, the company can file an application – the New Drug Application (NDA) – to have the drug commercialized and available for clinical application.
[src:lead-optimization/drug-discovery] NDA status enables the FDA to examine all submitted data on the drug to reach a decision on whether to approve or not approve the drug candidate based on its safety, specificity of effect, and efficacy of doses.
[src:lead-optimization/hit-to-lead] The hit to lead stage starts with confirmation and evaluation of the initial screening hits and is followed by synthesis of analogs (hit expansion).
[src:lead-optimization/hit-to-lead] Typically the initial screening hits display binding affinities for their biological target in the micromolar (10−6 molar concentration) range.
[src:lead-optimization/hit-to-lead] Through limited H2L optimization, the affinities of the hits are often improved by several orders of magnitude to the nanomolar (10−9 M) range.
[src:lead-optimization/hit-to-lead] The hits also undergo limited optimization to improve metabolic half life so that the compounds can be tested in animal models of disease and also to improve selectivity against other biological targets binding that may result in undesirable side effects.
[src:lead-optimization/hit-to-lead] On average, only one in every 5,000 compounds that enters drug discovery to the stage of preclinical development becomes an approved drug.
[src:lead-optimization/hit-to-lead] Following hit confirmation, several compound clusters will be chosen according to their characteristics in the previously defined tests.
[src:lead-optimization/hit-to-lead] The project team will usually select between three and six compound series to be further explored.
[src:lead-optimization/hit-to-lead] The next step will allow the testing of analogous compounds to determine a quantitative structure-activity relationship (QSAR).
[src:lead-optimization/hit-to-lead] Analogs can be quickly selected from an internal library or purchased from commercially available sources ("SAR by catalog" or "SAR by purchase").
[src:lead-optimization/hit-to-lead] Medicinal chemists will also start synthesizing related compounds using different methods such as combinatorial chemistry, high-throughput chemistry, or more classical organic chemistry synthesis.
[src:lead-optimization/hit-to-lead] The objective of this drug discovery phase is to synthesize lead compounds, new analogs with improved potency, reduced off-target activities, and physiochemical/metabolic properties suggestive of reasonable *in vivo* pharmacokinetics.
[src:lead-optimization/hit-to-lead] This optimization is accomplished through chemical modification of the hit structure, with modifications chosen by employing knowledge of the structure–activity relationship (SAR) as well as structure-based design if structural information about the target is available.
[src:lead-optimization/hit-to-lead] Lead optimization is concerned with experimental testing and confirmation of the compound based on animal efficacy models and ADMET (*in vitro* and *in situ*) tools that may be followed by target identification and target validation.
[src:lead-optimization/hit-to-lead] For educational purposes the European Federation for Medicinal Chemistry and Chemical Biology (EFMC) shared a series of webinars including 'Best Practices for Hit Finding' as well as 'Hit Generation Case Studies'.
[src:lead-optimization/lead-compound] The chemical structure serves as a starting point for chemical modifications in order to improve potency, selectivity, or pharma­co­kinetic parameters.
[src:lead-optimization/lead-compound] Furthermore, newly-invented pharma­co­logically active moieties may have poor druglikeness and may require chemical modification to become "drug-like" enough to be tested biologically or clinically.
[src:lead-optimization/lead-compound] Lead compounds are sometimes called *developmental candidates*.
[src:lead-optimization/lead-compound] This is because the discovery and selection of lead compounds occurs prior to preclinical and clinical development of the candidate.
[src:lead-optimization/lead-compound] Before lead compounds can be discovered, a suitable target for rational drug design must be selected on the basis of biological plausibility, or identified through screening potential lead compounds against multiple targets.
[src:lead-optimization/lead-compound] Drug libraries are often tested by high-throughput screenings (active compounds are designated as "hits") which can screen compounds for their ability to inhibit (antagonize) or stimulate (agonize) a target of interest as well as determine selectivity for these targets.
[src:lead-optimization/lead-compound] A lead compound may arise from a variety of different sources.
[src:lead-optimization/lead-compound] Lead compounds are found by characterizing natural products, employing combinatorial chemistry, or by molecular modeling as in rational drug design.
[src:lead-optimization/lead-compound] Chemicals identified as "hits" through high-throughput screening may also become lead compounds.
[src:lead-optimization/lead-compound] Once a lead compound is selected, it must undergo lead optimization, which involves making the compound more "drug-like." This is where Lipinski's rule of five comes into play, sometimes also referred to as the "Pfizer rule" or simply as the "rule of five".
[src:lead-optimization/lead-compound] Other factors, such as the ease of scaling up the manufacturing of the chemical, must be taken into consideration as well.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] Medicinal chemistry is a basically interdisciplinary science combining organic chemistry with biochemistry, computational chemistry, pharmacology, molecular biology, statistics, and physical chemistry.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] Medicines can also be inorganic and organometallic compounds, commonly referred to as metallodrugs (e.g., platinum, lithium and gallium-based agents such as cisplatin, lithium carbonate and gallium nitrate, respectively).
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] The discipline of Medicinal Inorganic Chemistry investigates the role of metals in medicine metallotherapeutics, which involves the study and treatment of diseases and health conditions associated with inorganic metals in biological systems.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] There are several metallotherapeutics approved for the treatment of cancer (e.g., contain Pt, Ru, Gd, Ti, Ge, V, and Ga), antimicrobials (e.g., Ag, Cu, and Ru), diabetes (e.g., V and Cr), broad-spectrum antibiotic (e.g., Bi), bipolar disorder (e.g., Li).
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] Other areas of study include: metallomics, genomics, proteomics, diagnostic agents (e.g., MRI: Gd, Mn; X-ray: Ba, I) and radiopharmaceuticals (e.g., 99mTc for diagnostics, 186Re for therapeutics).
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] Practically speaking, it involves chemical aspects of identification, and then systematic, thorough synthetic alteration of new chemical entities to make them suitable for therapeutic use.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] It includes synthetic and computational aspects of the study of existing drugs and agents in development in relation to their bioactivities (biological activities and properties), i.e., understanding their structure–activity relationships (SAR).
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] Pharmaceutical chemistry is focused on quality aspects of medicines and aims to assure fitness for purpose of medicinal products.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] Discovery is the identification of novel active chemical compounds, often called "hits", which are typically found by assay of compounds for a desired biological activity.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] Initial hits can come from repurposing existing agents toward a new pathologic processes, and from observations of biologic effects of new or existing natural products from bacteria, fungi, plants, etc.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] In addition, hits also routinely originate from structural observations of small molecule "fragments" bound to therapeutic targets (enzymes, receptors, etc.), where the fragments serve as starting points to develop more chemically complex forms by synthesis.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] While a number of approaches toward the identification and development of hits exist, the most successful techniques are based on chemical and biological intuition developed in team environments through years of rigorous practice aimed solely at discovering new therapeutic agents.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] The final synthetic chemistry stages involve the production of a lead compound in suitable quantity and quality to allow large scale animal testing, and then human clinical trials.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] This involves the optimization of the synthetic route for bulk industrial production, and discovery of the most suitable drug formulation.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] The former of these is still the bailiwick of medicinal chemistry, the latter brings in the specialization of formulation science (with its components of physical and polymer chemistry and materials science).
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] Critical at this stage is the transition to more stringent GMP requirements for material sourcing, handling, and chemistry.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] The synthetic methodology employed in medicinal chemistry is subject to constraints that do not apply to traditional organic synthesis.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] Owing to the prospect of scaling the preparation, safety is of paramount importance.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] The potential toxicity of reagents affects methodology.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] The structures of pharmaceuticals are assessed in many ways, in part as a means to predict efficacy, stability, and accessibility.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] Lipinski's rule of five focus on the number of hydrogen bond donors and acceptors, number of rotatable bonds, surface area, and lipophilicity.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] Other parameters by which medicinal chemists assess or classify their compounds are: synthetic complexity, chirality, flatness, and aromatic ring count.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] Structural analysis of lead compounds is often performed through computational methods prior to actual synthesis of the ligand(s).
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] This is done for a number of reasons, including but not limited to: time and financial considerations (expenditure, etc.).
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] Once the ligand of interest has been synthesized in the laboratory, analysis is then performed by traditional methods (TLC, NMR, GC/MS, and others).
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] Medicinal chemistry is by nature an interdisciplinary science, and practitioners have a strong background in organic chemistry, which must eventually be coupled with a broad understanding of biological concepts related to cellular drug targets.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] Scientists in medicinal chemistry work are principally industrial scientists (but see following), working as part of an interdisciplinary team that uses their chemistry abilities, especially, their synthetic abilities, to use chemical principles to design effective therapeutic agents.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] The length of training is intense, with practitioners often required to attain a 4-year bachelor's degree followed by a 4–6 year Ph.D. in organic chemistry.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] Most training regimens also include a postdoctoral fellowship period of 2 or more years after receiving a Ph.D. in chemistry, making the total length of training range from 10 to 12 years of college education.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] However, employment opportunities at the Master's level also exist in the pharmaceutical industry, and at that and the Ph.D. level there are further opportunities for employment in academia and government.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] Graduate level programs in medicinal chemistry can be found in traditional medicinal chemistry or pharmaceutical sciences departments, both of which are traditionally associated with schools of pharmacy, and in some chemistry departments.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] However, the majority of working medicinal chemists have graduate degrees (MS, but especially Ph.D.) in organic chemistry, rather than medicinal chemistry, and the preponderance of positions are in research, where the net is necessarily cast widest, and most broad synthetic activity occurs.
[src:lead-optimization/medicinal-chemistry] In research of small molecule therapeutics, an emphasis on training that provides for breadth of synthetic experience and "pace" of bench operations is clearly present (e.g., for individuals with pure synthetic organic and natural products synthesis in Ph.D. and post-doctoral positions, ibid.).
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] A **prodrug** is a pharmacologically inactive medication or compound that, after intake, is metabolized (i.e., converted within the body) into a pharmacologically active drug.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] Instead of administering a drug directly, a corresponding prodrug can be used to improve how the drug is absorbed, distributed, metabolized, and excreted (ADME).
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] Prodrugs are often designed to improve bioavailability when a drug itself is poorly absorbed from the gastrointestinal tract.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] A prodrug may be used to improve how selectively the drug interacts with cells or processes that are not its intended target.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] This reduces adverse or unintended effects of a drug, especially important in treatments like chemotherapy, which can have severe unintended and undesirable side effects.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] Many herbal extracts historically used in medicine contain glycosides (sugar derivatives) of the active agent, which are hydrolyzed in the intestines to release the active and more bioavailable aglycone.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] For example, salicin is a β-D-glucopyranoside that is cleaved by esterases to release salicylic acid.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] Aspirin (acetylsalicylic acid), first made by Felix Hoffmann at Bayer in 1897, is a synthetic prodrug of salicylic acid.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] However, in other cases, such as codeine and morphine, the administered drug is enzymatically activated to form sugar derivatives (morphine-glucuronides) that are more active than the parent compound.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] The first synthetic antimicrobial drug, arsphenamine, discovered in 1909 by Sahachiro Hata in the laboratory of Paul Ehrlich, is not toxic to bacteria until it has been converted to an active form by the body.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] Likewise, prontosil, the first sulfa drug (discovered by Gerhard Domagk in 1932), must be cleaved in the body to release the active molecule, sulfanilamide.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] Since that time, many other examples have been identified.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] Terfenadine, the first non-sedating antihistamine, had to be withdrawn from the market because of the small risk of a serious side effect.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] However, terfenadine was discovered to be the prodrug of the active molecule, fexofenadine, which does not carry the same risks as the parent compound.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] Therefore, fexofenadine could be placed on the market as a safe replacement for the original drug.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] Loratadine, another non-sedating antihistamine, is the prodrug of desloratadine, which is largely responsible for the antihistaminergic effects of the parent compound.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] However, in this case the parent compound does not have the side effects associated with terfenadine, and so both loratadine and its active metabolite, desloratadine, are currently marketed.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] Approximately 10% of all marketed drugs worldwide can be considered prodrugs.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] Since 2008, at least 30 prodrugs have been approved by the FDA.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] Seven prodrugs were approved in 2015 and six in 2017.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] Both major types can be further categorized into subtypes, based on factors such as (Type I) whether the intracellular bioactivation location is also the site of therapeutic action, or (Type 2) whether or not bioactivation occurs in the gastrointestinal fluids or in the circulation system.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] Type IA prodrugs include many antimicrobial and chemotherapy agents (e.g., 5-flurouracil).
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] Type IB agents rely on metabolic enzymes, especially in hepatic cells, to bioactivate the prodrugs intracellularly to active drugs.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] Importantly, prodrugs can belong to multiple subtypes (i.e., Mixed-Type).
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] A Mixed-Type prodrug is one that is bioactivated at multiple sites, either in parallel or sequential steps.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] For example, a prodrug, which is bioactivated concurrently in both target cells and metabolic tissues, could be designated as a "Type IA/IB" prodrug (e.g., HMG Co-A reductase inhibitors and some chemotherapy agents; note the symbol " / " applied here).
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] When a prodrug is bioactivated sequentially, for example initially in GI fluids then systemically within the target cells, it is designated as a "Type IIA-IA" prodrug (e.g., tenofovir disoproxil; note the symbol " - " applied here).
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] Many antibody- virus- and gene-directed enzyme prodrug therapies (ADEPTs, VDEPTs, GDEPTs) and proposed nanoparticle- or nanocarrier-linked drugs can understandably be Sequential Mixed-Type prodrugs.
[src:lead-optimization/prodrug] To differentiate these two Subtypes, the symbol dash " - " is used to designate and to indicate sequential steps of bioactivation, and is meant to distinguish from the symbol slash " / " used for the Parallel Mixed-Type prodrugs.
[src:lead-optimization/structure-activity-relationship] The **structure–activity relationship** (**SAR**) is the relationship between the chemical structure of a molecule and its biological activity.
[src:lead-optimization/structure-activity-relationship] This idea was first presented by Alexander Crum Brown and Thomas Richard Fraser at least as early as 1868.
[src:lead-optimization/structure-activity-relationship] The analysis of SAR enables the determination of the chemical group responsible for evoking a target biological effect in the organism.
[src:lead-optimization/structure-activity-relationship] This allows modification of the effect or the potency of a bioactive compound (typically a drug) by changing its chemical structure.
[src:lead-optimization/structure-activity-relationship] Medicinal chemists use the techniques of chemical synthesis to insert new chemical groups into the biomedical compound and test the modifications for their biological effects.
[src:lead-optimization/structure-activity-relationship] This method was refined to build mathematical relationships between the chemical structure and the biological activity, known as quantitative structure–activity relationships (QSAR).
[src:lead-optimization/structure-activity-relationship] A related term is structure affinity relationship (SAFIR).
[src:lead-optimization/structure-activity-relationship] The large number of synthetic organic chemicals currently in production presents a major challenge for timely collection of detailed environmental data on each compound.
[src:lead-optimization/structure-activity-relationship] The concept of structure biodegradability relationships (SBR) has been applied to explain variability in persistence among organic chemicals in the environment.
[src:lead-optimization/structure-activity-relationship] Early attempts generally consisted of examining the degradation of a homologous series of structurally related compounds under identical conditions with a complex "universal" inoculum, typically derived from numerous sources.
[src:lead-optimization/structure-activity-relationship] This approach revealed that the nature and positions of substituents affected the apparent biodegradability of several chemical classes, with resulting general themes, such as halogens generally conferring persistence under aerobic conditions.
[src:lead-optimization/structure-activity-relationship] Subsequently, more quantitative approaches have been developed using principles of QSAR and often accounting for the role of sorption (bioavailability) in chemical fate.
